name: Laura Vater
bio: GI oncologist, writer, mother, TEDx speaker, & advocate for compassion & clinician health // Sharing encouragement, insights, & health tips :)

social_posts.post_text:
Hi, and welcome to my page! I’m Laura Vater (vah-der, rhymes with water), and I’m so glad you’re here.
 
I’m a medical oncologist and writer, and I believe patients deserve to be treated as whole human beings, and that all clinicians deserve the same. 
 
On this page, you’ll see content about the mental and physical health of clinicians, inspiration for those in the field/in school or training, and some tools I’ve found useful for holding onto health, joy, meaning, and empathy in the medical profession.
 
Here are a few other things about me:

1️⃣ I married my husband, Kevin, right before med school, and we have a spunky 6-year old daughter who was born during my MS4 year. We also have a furry, peanut-butter-loving golden retriever named Sanibel 🐕 
2️⃣ I’ve been working on a novel for the last four years about a medical resident (more to come soon!), and my goal is to start looking for an agent in mid-May (fingers-crossed!)
3️⃣ My favorite things are: good books, loose-leaf tea, twinkle lights, colorful mugs, long walks, flowering trees, state and National parks, hot baths, and pet therapy. 
 
I would love for you to introduce yourself below and tell me some of your favorite things! 
 
And whether you’re a new face or OG friend, I genuinely appreciate that you’re here, and hope you’ll find some encouragement on this page 🤍

Nearly half of medical students have anxiety. I did too, but never talked about. I was too ashamed. 

If you’re experiencing this, please know:
You are not defective. 
You do not lack resilience. 
You are not weak. 

If you’ve ever faced anxiety, what has helped you?

—
And THANK YOU to @indy_firm for inviting me to speak today! 

#medschool #medstudent #anxiety

People are going to have all sorts of opinions about you, especially if you’re a woman. Especially if you choose to have a child during medical training. But make the decisions that are right for you and your family anyway. 

When someone tells you that you can’t do something, please just keep right on going. 🤍

Women in medicine, what have people said to you about your choice to either have (or not have) children? 

#womeninmedicine

So honored & humbled to have spoken on the TEDx stage at Rush University last night about how exhaustion kills compassion.

Without sleep, the empathy parts of our brain don’t work very well. Our compassion fades when we’re exhausted. If you’re feeling this, know you’re not alone. Sleep is not optional for any of us, including doctors. 

A huge thank you to the organizers of this @tedxrushu event, the other speakers, and all of you who came! It was so nice to meet many of you 😊

Together, we can make the field of medicine more human, for patients and clinicians 🤍

#tedx #humanisminmedicine

Just a reminder to attendings, fellows, & residents: Let your med students leave early if you can. Give them time to study, to exercise, to be with family, or to simply rest. They need that.

Tweet by my kind & brilliant friend @lilaflavin

There’s a link here we don’t talk about enough—the link between being dehumanized yourself and then having lowered empathy for other humans. It’s hard to care deeply for others when your own humanity is being ignored. 

At the core of the field of medicine should be respect for human life, for patients, learners, and seasoned practitioners alike.

Let’s bring more humanity back into the field of medicine, through connection & time with patients, valuing & protecting our learners, providing mental health support, and ensuring adequate rest and time off. 

What would you add?

If you were mistreated or bullied in your education, training, or workplace, it may be hard to watch things improve for others.

Even so, this is how we improve things. We create a culture of learning we wish we’d had.

If you were bullied, create a bully-free culture, where none of that is tolerated.

If you were ignored, make your learners feel valued.

If your health & wellbeing wasn’t prioritized, find ways to promote the health of learners.

-
How are your making things better for your learners? (and thank you for doing so 🙏)

—

Happy Friday (!!) & wishing you this level of confidence as you finish up the week (or plow right into a weekend of work). Thanks for all you do. 

Hope this makes you laugh a little like it did me 💛

When I developed anxiety in med school, I felt defective. Weak. As if I didn’t belong. 

May is mental health awareness month, & I hope you know this: If your mental health has declined, you are not weak. You’re a human being.

I’ll be sharing lots of resources this month (that I wish I would’ve know about in my training) to help anyone else going through this. 🤍

#mentalhealthawarenessmonth

When I graduated from med school, I was so nervous for intern year & had all these feelings of inadequacy: 

Was I really prepared? Did I know enough? Would I make the right decisions for my patients?

To all of you graduating this month, please remember to be kind to yourself. You are prepared. You are ready. Your job is not to know everything. Your job is to keep learning and to care deeply for your patients.

Enjoy this month. Take a deep breath. Believe in your capabilities. You are qualified for this next step. 🤍

—
Are you graduating this month? How are you feeling?

Thank you to the University of Minnesota Medical School students who wanted ME of all people to give their commencement address today.

Congratulations, new doctors! And to all the medical students graduating this month! 

Remember that you are more than a career, you are a human being. And hold onto your empathy with both hands 🤍

I started my first month as an intern in the intensive care unit, and I was terrified… How could I care for these critically ill patients? What if I didn’t know enough?

On the drive home each day, I sat in silence trying to process everything I had witnessed and learned that day. And it was a lot. And I made it through. And so will you. 

To all the new doctors: Your job is not to know everything. Your job is to show up & ask questions. To learn something new each day. And to care deeply for your patients. You will be ok. 🩵

—

I will never forget the moment when my attending (when I was a fellow) squatted next to a patient in pain, held his hand, and made a clear statement of support. That moment will always stay with me and influence how I care for patients in similar circumstances.

Compassion is modeled. It is in many ways taught. So is the absence of compassion. May we continue to care even when we cannot heal, and continue to model this for others.

Have you had a similar mentor or experience in healthcare? What did the person do?

—
Tweet: Dr. Sangarlangkar

My internal dialogue this week after FINALLY making time to see a primary care physician for a check up after years without one (and despite being an internal med/oncology trained doctor)…

Just a reminder that you are worthy of the time it takes to prioritize your health. You’re a human too. 🤍

—

Are you finally getting your checkups? Going to therapy? Send some words of encouragement to those who might need it👇

I became a mom in med school. I became a mom at a time when many people told me I shouldn’t (or couldn’t) do it.

Being a med student (then resident) and a mom was challenging. Perhaps the biggest challenge I’ve faced in life thus far. But it was possible. And messy. And meaningful.

So to anyone being told they have to put their life (and plans to be a parent) on hold until training is done, don’t listen. This narrative is not helpful. We need more representation of parents in training, and more support.

Sending love to all the moms out there on Mother’s Day, especially those who are in training. You are doing something so hard and beautiful 🤍

A wise mentor told me before med school, “There is no perfect time to become a mother. Do it when you’re ready, regardless of what others say.”

I’m grateful for this advice everyday. It’s unfair to ask women in medicine to forgo childbearing in their key reproductive years. (And I have too many friends dealing with infertility now because of this). 

We can and should do much more to support parents in medical training.

(And stepping of my soap box now)

—

The reason that women are less likely to be credited is “because their work is often not known, is not appreciated, or is ignored.”

Women deserve as much credit for their scientific work as men. Period.

To the doctors and doctors in training strugling with their mental health:

You cannot pour from an empty cup. You’ve devoted your lives to helping others but you cannot help others without first taking care of yourself.

There is nothing shameful about therapy, medications and doing what you need to do to get better. 

Rely on others who are there to support you. This does not make you weak. It makes you human to want support from others.

You are not weak or any less competent of a physician because you struggle with your mental health.

Rooting for you today, tomorrow, and every day that you need the encouragement.

You are amazing. We hope you give yourself more credit today.

New data from nearly 5,000 PGY-2 residents: Long hours and extended shifts are not good for patients or for doctors.

The combination of long hours (≥60 per week) and extended shifts (≥24 hours) has a synergistic effect, amplifying medical error, car crashes, and needle sticks.

It’s time to rethink the way we’ve always done things. Residents need reasonable hours and adequate rest to protect patients and themselves.

What are your thoughts on this?

#meded #residentdoctor 

—
Source: 
Barger LK, Weaver MD, Sullivan JP, et al Impact of work schedules of senior resident physicians on patient and resident physician safety: nationwide, prospective cohort study BMJ Medicine 2023;2:e000320.

Shout out to all pediatricians today. You are doing such important work for our world. 🙌

Hold on, friends in training, more time is coming. More weekends. More slow, peaceful days. More moments with the people you love.

Recently I met a patient who felt abandoned by his previous doctors when he opted for no chemo. When I said I’d be happy to keep seeing him, no matter what he decided, this brought him to tears.

Our patients need our support and guidance, no matter what decisions they make. This is called nonabandonment—and it’s a central ethical principal.

Thanks to all of you that make similar decisions. What does this look like in your practice?

TW: suicide. Rest in peace, Dr. Nakita Mortimer, who was an anesthesia resident and advocate for better working conditions for resident physicians.

This is devastating news, and we must continue to improve the working conditions for resident doctors.

Her friend and co-resident @dr.rehema said: “This loss has been a harsh reminder that ‘checking in on your strong friends’ isn't enough. We need systemic and institutional changes to support our medical trainees who are struggling. We feel such a fire to continue to fight for change. To fight like Nakita fought... and I hope Nakita inspires you to fight, too.”

—

To all the new interns: I hope you’ll remember this when you feel overwhelmed. Your job is not to know everything. If you did, you wouldn’t need to go through residency. 

Trust that you’re prepared. Trust that the daily learning will compound. You’re ready for what comes next.

Who’s starting intern year soon? How are you feeling? We are rooting for you!

Remember this when all the others tell you otherwise. They told me, "You can't be a good doctor and a good mother."

Thanks to @medpage for publishing my essay on this 🙏

Were you told something similar?

—
Article: Why can’t I be both a good doctor and a good mother?

There are going to be incredible wins in our careers, wins where we help someone feel better, or decrease the chance of their cancer coming back, or make them feel supported and less afraid. 
 
These successes will not be published in the medical literature. They will not result in awards, fame, or wealth. 

They may be as simple as a patient who gives you a thank you card or a leftover muffin from her hospital breakfast tray; it maybe a patient who trusts you with information she can’t tell anyone else. 
 
These are the moments that will sustain you.

—
Have you had a moment in your work that has helped sustain you?

Just a reminder that it takes a lot of time & effort to get to a doctor’s office, & most people will feel some anxiety about what might be found (or even how they’ll be treated).

Our kindness and compassion go a long way in making the time and visit worth it, and to make our patients feel at ease.

Thanks for caring for others today.
(And thankfully everything is fine).

—

Getting sappy here because we’re celebrating 10 years of marriage today! So much has happened over the last decade, and last night we were talking about our best marriage advice…

1. Share inside jokes. Lots of them. 
2. Don’t make big decisions or argue when you’re hungry or tired. 
3. Celebrate your partner’s wins as your own.
4. Support their interests & hobbies as they evolve over time.
5. If you’re upset, say so. Be open & don’t hide how you feel.
6. Try to laugh together everyday.
7. Plan trips, dates, & other things to look forward to. 
8. Say thank you, I’m sorry, and I love you often!

What would you add?

Four years ago I had suicidal ideation due to repeated sleep deprivation at work. I was a resident working long hours, including 28-hour calls. 

One doctor dies by suicide each day in the US. Sleep deprivation contributes to this—it’s an independent risk factor. We cannot say we care about resident wellness, or physician mental health without talking about sleep deprivation.

Sleep is an essential, not optional, part of medical training, and of life. We cannot safely practice medicine or care for ourselves without sleep.

—
Have you ever experienced a decline in your health related to sleep loss?

Saying, “I don’t know, but I will find out,” can be an important way to build trust with patients. If I don’t know something (for example, how a certain supplement or alternative treatment may affect my patient’s care), I’ll often look it up with my patients in the room. If it’s something more complex, I tell them I’ll need to chat with a pharmacist or other expert.

It’s better to be honest and build trust than to pretend we know something when we don’t.

What have your experiences of this been like?

Or a resident supervising interns for the first time overwhelmed trying to keep everything straight. Or a new fellow with a tired brain after clinic while also studying for boards. As July comes to a close, I can’t help but reflect on all the (hypothetical) safety concerns with new interns… but what about the safety of patients being treated by sleep deprived doctors all year long?

Sleep deprivation reduces attention, concentration, and memory recall. It increases the risk of medical error, as well as car accidents and needle sticks among clinicians.

If our goals are to improve patient safety and support the health of clinicians, we need to reconsider the antiquated model of sleep deprivation in medical training and practice.

What are your thoughts on this?

——

References (per the CDC):

1. Williamson AM, Feyer AM. Moderate sleep deprivation produces impairments in cognitive and motor performance equivalent to legally prescribed levels of alcohol intoxication. Occup Environ Med. 2000;57(10):649-55.
2. Arnedt JT, Wilde GJ, Munt PW, MacLean AW. How do prolonged wakefulness and alcohol compare in the decrements they produce on a simulated driving task? Accid Anal Prev. 2001;33(3):337-44.
3. Dawson D, Reid K. Fatigue, alcohol and performance impairment. Nature. 1997;388(6639):235.
4. Lamond N, Dawson D. Quantifying the performance impairment associated with fatigue. J Sleep Res. 1999;8(4):255-62.

When I worked weekends when my daughter was little, she’d cry & scream when I left. Now at 7, she kisses both my hands, hugs me, & plans a fun date with Dad 🥰

4 phrases to repeat to yourself as a new school year begins: 

1. I am not stupid, I’m just learning something new. And learning takes time. I will be kind to myself along this journey. 

2. What I’m doing matters, and even so: I am more than a score, more than a grade, more than a degree, more than a career.

3. It’s okay that this feels overwhelming right now. All new things do. But I’ll keep at it. I won’t give up.

4. I’m proud of myself for learning something new. I’m proud of myself for showing up. All of this takes courage.

—
I hope these words resonate with you in some way, and sending you peace as a new school year begins. 🤍

This week, Dr. Krystal Cascetta, an oncologist, died by suicide and sadly took the life of her 4-month-old daughter. 

She was likely experiencing postpartum psychosis, according to experts.

We do not fully know the factors and circumstances that led to her death. Postpartum depression affects about 1 in 7 women, and postpartum psychosis affects fewer than 5% of new moms. This can lead to hallucinations, feeling confused and lost, paranoia, and even attempts to harm yourself or your child. 

We also don’t know if sleep loss related to her work contributed to her decline in mental health. 

It’s essential that we support the mental health of all doctors, especially those who are postpartum.

For me, my daughter was colicky from 2 weeks to 2 months of age. That was the most difficult stretch of my life. I was sleeping very little. I was run down. There were times I had intrusive thoughts. We must support new mothers. We must support the mental health of all doctors.

Even short bouts of activity may lower your risk of cancer and extend your life! VILPA, or Vigorous Intensity Lifestyle Physical Activity is brief (1-2 min), sporadic exercise during daily life, such as power walking on the way to work, doing stairs, or even carrying groceries. Even small amounts of VILPA may lower your risk of cancer and extend your life.

In the Nature article below, they found that VILPA duration of ~ 4.4 min per day was associated with a 26%–30% reduction in all-cause and cancer mortality risk and a 32%–34% reduction in CVD mortality risk.

While these studies are observational (meaning they can’t prove cause and effect), there was also a recent analysis providing evidence of a causal association between vigorous physical activity and breast cancer (article 3 below).

References:

Stamatakis E, Ahmadi MN, Friedenreich CM, et al. Vigorous Intermittent Lifestyle Physical Activity and Cancer Incidence Among Nonexercising Adults: The UK Biobank Accelerometry Study. JAMA Oncol. Published online July 27, 2023. doi:10.1001/jamaoncol.2023.1830

Stamatakis, E., Ahmadi, M.N., Gill, J.M.R. et al. Association of wearable device-measured vigorous intermittent lifestyle physical activity with mortality. Nat Med 28, 2521–2529 (2022). https://doi.org/10.1038/s41591-022-02100-x

Dixon-Suen  SC�, Lewis  SJ�, Martin  RM�,  et al; Breast Cancer Association Consortium.  Physical activity, sedentary time and breast cancer risk: a Mendelian randomisation study. �  Br J Sports Med. 2022;56(20):1157-1170.

One year as an attending (!) and here are 5 things I’ve learned:

1. Deep connection with patients will sustain you. It makes the work worth doing.

2. Patients will die unexpectedly. And this will devastate you. You’ll go back and re-check every dose, every lab, every decision you made, and there often will STILL be no clear reason why. This will be the hardest aspect of the job, and you will never forget these patients.

3. No matter how much time you spend with a patient, no matter how much compassion you show, no matter how much you support them, you CANNOT please everyone. There are patients who will want a different doctor than you sometimes. Try not to take this personally.

4. Insurance companies and prior auths will waste your time and frustrate you beyond belief. Try to remember the patient underneath it all, and work to change the system.

5. Nearly all patients appreciate honest information about their prognosis, even when dealing with something really hard, like metastatic cancer. Even better if you can deliver it in a caring, jargon-free way, then support them through their emotions & help them navigate the decisions.

What did you learn your first year as an attending? Please share your wisdom with us :) 

#oneyearanniversary #attendinglife

I get questions about this ALL THE TIME. Here’s what we know about drinking very hot liquids and esophageal SQUAMOUS CELL carcinoma. 

The WHO classifies consuming very hot beverages as a class 2A carcinogen, or probably carcinogenic to humans. This is based on studies done in Iran, China, Turkey, and South America where people more frequently drink very hot beverages. To my knowledge, large studies haven’t been done in the US (and in the US, it’s esophageal ADENOCARCINOMA that’s more common, and hot beverages are not thought to affect risk of this type). 

The WHO lists a possible mechanism that hot liquids can cause esophageal injury, and it’s possible that the trauma leads to cell changes and cancer.

In some studies, people drinking beverages > 60 degrees Celsius (140 degrees Fahrenheit) may have increased risk, compared to those who drink beverages at cooler temperatures. These studies were not perfect. They also were mainly cohort or retrospective studies. 

Remember: association doesn’t prove causation. 

Given this data, it’s reasonable to avoid drinking piping hot liquid. If you let your drink cool for a few minutes before sipping it, or add cold milk, it’s unlikely that you’re increasing your risk of esophageal cancer.

Even more importantly, here are bigger things you can do to reduce your risk of esophageal SCC: Quit smoking and cut down on how much alcohol you drink.

Studies:

Islami F, Poustchi H, Pourshams A, et al. A prospective study of tea drinking temperature and risk of esophageal squamous cell carcinoma. Int J Cancer. 2020;146(1):18-25.

Lin S, Xu G, Chen Z, et al. Tea drinking and the risk of esophageal cancer: focus on tea type and drinking temperature. Eur J Cancer Prev. 2020;29(5):382-387. 

More from WHO: https://www.iarc.who.int/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/pr244_E.pdf

#cancer #esophagealcancer #hottea #coffee

This week, Dr. Corban Caldwell, an Emergency Medicine resident, died in a car crash, leaving behind his wife and five children. 

Per police reports, around 2:45 a.m., his car left the interstate and struck several trees.

We don’t fully know the factors that led to his death. We also don’t know if sleep deprivation contributed to this accident. 

We do know that the chance of getting in a car crash increases with sleep loss, and that when a sleep-deprived resident drives home after a long shift, the chance of being involved in a motor vehicle accident increases by 168%.

Please consider supporting Dr. Caldwell’s GoFundMe page to support his family: https://www.gofundme.com/f/sv2nzu-the-caldwell-family

And if you’re ever finishing a shift late at night or after getting little sleep, please consider taking a nap before driving, or getting a ride home. 

—
Data in slides from Dr. Matthew Walker’s book, Why We Sleep.

My daughter was an infant when I applied for residency, & here are 4 things I wish I knew back then:

1. You should choose a program that’s a good fit for YOU. Ask about things that matter to YOU. (e.g., Will you have access to a mentor in your field of interest? What’s the call schedule like? Is there home call? Is there opt-out counseling? Are there rooms to pump if you’re breastfeeding?)

2. It’s okay to prioritize matching near your family, friends, or community. Don’t feel guilty about this. Having support during training is such a gift, especially if you have kids. 

3. In the same breath, it’s okay to want to move somewhere new, try a new location, have a fresh start. Don’t feel guilty for wanting to move for your dream program or location. 

4. This process and the uncertainty wrapped around it is stressful, so be kind to yourself. Remember that we all could likely be happy at a number of programs, and no place is perfect.

—

When we alter our faces with filters (even subtly) it makes us like our real faces less. It makes us think about all the things we need to “fix” about them. At least for me. 

And by age 13, 80% of girls have downloaded a filter or used an app to change how they look. My daughter is 7, and this got me thinking: Do I really want to send her the message that her mom is not happy with how she looks? 

All of us want to put our best face forward online, especially for those of you getting older (like me) and face long shifts or exhaustion from parenthood.

But I’ve learned that filters make us dissatisfied with our natural faces. So I did a little experiment. What would happen if I just stopped swiping to use those filters?

These three things happened when I stopped using face filters online:

1. I got some unwanted messages (mostly from men) about how my face looked tired, or that I needed Botox or eye cream. 
2. I started liking my unfiltered face in the mirror more.
3. I stopped being so hard on myself for not having perfect skin & stopped reading too much into the ads targeting me for skin products, fillers, etc. 

It’s a process, that’s for sure. And here’s to an intention to show up more unfiltered online. 🤍

What are your thoughts on this? How do face filters make you feel about yourself?

Recently I told a patient his cancer had come back. It was now stage 4 and the tools we have couldn’t cure it. I sat with him and his family as they processed and grieved. As they cried. As I cried.

Then I walked into the next patient’s room as if nothing had happened. And the day went on like this.

This is just a reminder that our jobs are not normal. The things we deal with on a daily basis are not normal. We witness illness, and trauma, and death. We see patients at their most vulnerable. We help them navigate through hard decisions. We are sometimes with them in death. 

This work is sacred and hard. And it’s okay if it affects us. There’s no way we can do this work and not be affected. 

When you find yourself in moments of stillness, allow yourself to process. To feel. To cope. To breathe. And thanks for all you do. 🤍

What are the aspects of your job that are not “normal”?

Just a reminder that it’s okay to protect your time. It’s okay to set boundaries. It’s okay to say no.

In fact, this helps us prioritize our physical and mental health, our creativity, and our relationships. It protects our ability to do this work. 

How have you set healthy boundaries with work?

It’s National Physician Suicide Awareness Day, and 4 years ago, I was at a very low point. I had suicidal ideation due to repeated sleep deprivation—I was a resident working repeated 28-hour calls for many months in a row.
 
It’s hard to say this, but the only thing that kept me going was the mental image of my daughter’s face (she was 3 at the time) and the devastating thought of her growing up without a mother. 
 
Physicians have one of the highest suicide rates of any profession, and more than half of us know a doctor who has either considered, attempted or died by suicide. 
 
While 60% of physicians report feelings of burnout, only 19% seek mental health support. When left untreated, burnout can cause depression, anxiety, PTSD and substance misuse. It can lead to suicidal thoughts among physicians. Lack of sleep contributes to this too.
 
40% of physicians are afraid or know another physician fearful of seeking mental health care because of intrusive licensing and credentialing applications.

Confidential help is available & YOU ARE NOT ALONE. Your life matters. Text “SCRUBS” to 741741 or call the Physician Support Line at 1-888-409-0141, or reach out to me on here. 🤍

#npsaday

If you ever see a person hurting, trust your instincts. Talk to them, comfort them, be there.

For the first few days on my Gyn onc rotation in med school, all I did was the shadow the doctor. I’d watch him dictate notes between surgeries. During that time, I didn’t think I could be beside the patient, talking to them or comforting them. I missed chances to help make them feel less alone, and I regret that. 

I made it a priority going forward to focus on my patients as much as I could during medical training. To pay attention to their body language, to talk to them, to support them, even if those around me weren’t used to the student doing that. 

Hold the hand of the patient who needs you, even when those around you don’t respond in the same way or understand.

Don’t worry what others think. Do what you can to help.

So much of showing compassion depends on simply paying attention and committing to taking action.

Hold onto your empathy with both hands.

Just a reminder that someone may look “fine“ and yet be facing anxiety, depression, or thoughts of suicide.

Especially in medical fields, we learn to pretend we’re okay when we’re not. We learn that being “strong” means suffering in silence.

At my lowest point of mental health, I still showed up to work & worked all day, everyday. I still worked the long calls. I still wrote the notes, and put in the orders, and completed my tasks. I didn’t tell any of my peers or mentors I was struggling, because I thought that would make me look weak or even interrupt my training.

Check in with your friends and colleagues. When you ask how they’re doing, take time to listen. Be vulnerable & open about your own challenges. 

And if you’re leading programs and teams, support the health of others by ensuring enough sleep and reasonable workloads. Offer things like opt-out counseling, debriefing sessions, honest town halls or small groups, and anonymous reporting. 

And most importantly, continue to create a culture where being “strong” doesn’t mean being “fine” all the time.

Thanks to everyone out there working hard to support the mental health of clinicians. 🙏

Here are 5 ways I’ve learned to carve out time for my patients, my family, & my mental & physical health:

1. Set the time you want to have with patients, even if that means going “against” what others do or what others are telling you to do. Even if that means you make less money. For me, that’s 60 minutes with each new patient & 30 minutes for follow up.

2. Choose how many days you want to work clinically & the times you want to work within that day. Again, you sacrifice money but gain time. For me, I’m in academics and have 3 clinical days and 2 days for writing, creative work, mentoring, teaching.

3. Take time off. Schedule vacation. Unplug. Be present. Don’t feel guilty for time away. It’s funny, whenever I’m going to be out of the office, my patients will say, “I’m so glad you get some time off. You need that.” 🥺

4. Try to eliminate rush from your days. This is hard especially in medicine. Give yourself some added time for the commute and make sure you’re not overbooked. Say no to other things that are good things but take time (I’m still working on this).

5. Do work at work as much as possible. Those messages, EMR inboxes, peer to peers… having a day that’s not over scheduled means I have more time to do those tasks in my normal day.

Would love to hear what works for you. How do you create a life in medicine that protects your time with your patients, family, and for your health?

#healthcareburnout #physicianwellness #physicianhealth

Yesterday I polled the primary care clinicians on here. The biggest frustration they face is not enough time with their patients, being pushed to move faster. Being called inefficient. 

Listening takes time. Compassion takes time. Thorough care takes time. 

There is no way to be the clinicians we want and need to be if we don’t have enough time with our patients. 

What are your thoughts on this?

#humanisminmedicine #compassionatepatientcare #primarycare

In my training, I’ve been on the primary team asking for support. I’ve also been the specialist called at 3 a.m.

I know this: Primary care teams are overworked. Specialists are overworked. Nurses are overworked. 

And even so, we improve healthcare a little more each time we treat our colleagues with respect. 🤍
Board certified 🙌 So grateful to have passed my oncology boards — this final step of my training. Thank you for your words of encouragement, your prayers, your kindness. It means so much to me. 🤍

The work we do is important, incredibly important. We can find meaning, connection, and value in our work. In the same breath, the work can be done by someone with equal talent. 

As hard as it is to say, we are replaceable at work. That doesn’t mean our care, connection, and compassion doesn’t deeply matter.

But we are never replaceable at home.

I hope this can be a reminder to you (and me) to be fully present at home as much as possible this holiday season 🤍

This season often brings back guilt from my time in training. Questions come up like: "Did I do enough? Was I there for my daughter enough? Was I a 'good' mother during my years of training?"

I've come to learn that this narrative isn't helpful. I did the best I could with the time I had back then. I missed holidays. We didn’t have time for all the festivities. I often didn’t have 6 hours to spare or the energy to bake cookies. But I loved my child. I wasn't perfect. I'm still not. I'm just a human being doing my best. I release the guilt from back then & I release it now.

Wishing you the same this holiday season 🤍

Merry Christmas from our family to yours! 🎄❤️

Sending you peace and love today. A special thanks to everyone who is working this holiday 🙏❤️

I used to feel such a scarcity of time, especially in my training. There was never enough time in the day. I was rushing from one thing to another, trying to get an impossible list of things done. Patient care, parenting tasks, research, modules… 

Now I'm in a season where I’m grateful for time. For less on my to-do list. For space to be at peace.

Wishing the same for you. Hoping that season arrives soon for you. 🤍

Dear med students: Even when it looks like your attendings are not affected by illness and death, we feel too. There is no way to do this work and not be impacted. 

We've just learned different ways to process and cope. That may be crying in the car, or the call room. It might be going for a walk. It might be through music, prayer, or therapy. 

No matter what it looks like, feel your emotions. Keep caring. And keep finding healthy ways to process and cope. 🤍

Burnout isn’t a badge of honor. And taking breaks is not only healthy, but also necessary for you to perform at your best self.

I can think of so many sick days during medical school and residency when I’d think to myself “man, I wish I just slowed down a little”.

So here’s your reminder: it’s okay to slow down. It’s okay to take a break. You are not in a race. Your health, both mental and physical, is worth prioritizing :)

The way you care for others with patience, non-judgment, and deep presence makes an impact on their care and in their lives. Never forget this. 🤍

Imagine this: You’ve been awake for 24 hours (or more). Your head hurts. Your eyes are dry. There’s a low-grade nausea in your stomach. 

And just as you’re about to put your head on the pillow, your phone chimes again: a new admission.

A human being sick enough to need hospital care, in need of a doctor who is rested and compassionate. 

Yet for the doctor, this patient represents another hour (or more) of work. The mirage of sleep has disappeared. A patient need representing the loss of sleep and health. 

This isn’t a model that builds empathy, but smashes it to the ground. 

We need to protect the sleep of our young doctors, to help protect their empathy, their health, and to ensure patients get the highest quality of care.

What are your thoughts on this?

—
